===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|blade}}, {{m|enm|blad}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|blæd||leaf}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*bladą}} (compare {{etyl|fy|-}} {{m|fy|bled}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{m|nl|blad}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{m|de|Blatt}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{m|da|blad}}) from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bʰlh̥₃oto}} (compare {{etyl|ga|-}} {{m|ga|bláth||flower}}, {{etyl|xto|-}} {{m|xto|pält}}, {{etyl|txb|-}} {{m|txb|pilta||leaf}}, {{etyl|sq|-}} {{m|sq|fletë||leaf}}), from {{m|ine-pro|*bʰleh₃-||to thrive, bloom}}. Similar usage in {{m|de|Sägeblatt||saw leaf}}, the German term for a saw blade. More at [[blow#Etymology_3|blow]].

